text.tspan: If CU is in Idle state then it will first check if the FIFO buffer has the capacity to store a Head Flit.
If No, then we need to wait till there is space. If Yes, then check if the Head Flit Buffer is empty.
If not, then do not receive a packet. This will lead to Head Of Line Blocking.
If it is empty, do Handshake and store the Head Flit in Head Flit Buffer as well as in the FIFO for the
subsequent routers to have head flit info. After head flit is received, Head Flit Status will be made 1 and
Until this becomes 0, no further flits will be accepted.
Head Flit will now be decoded by a decode logic to produce routing information.
After routing is done, HFB sends a Route Reservation Request to the Switch.
1. It checks if the path being requested is available or busy.
2. It checks for collision between incoming requests.
If both these conflicts are not present, the switch will reserve a path requested by the HFB.
Then it will send back an acknowledge signal if the route was reserved. There will be a timeout duration
during within which the Switch has to respond elseways, HFB considers that the request was not granted.
If the request is not granted then the HFB and Control FSM wait and resend the request after sometime.
If the request is granted, there is a burst of FIFO pops and data is sent to the receiving node via switch.
After the message is completely sent over a switch, that is, the router has successfully sent the tail packet,
a Relieving bit has to be sent to the Switch Control to relieve that path.

It will Stop receiving any other flit.
Head flit buffer is responsible for storing the head flit and it sends the head flit to the Decoder. The decoder then looks
at the Head Flit data and extracts the destination from it. Then it looks up for the destination in the Routing Table and
outputs the port to which this packet should be routed to so that it may reach its destination.
This way every possible Source-Destination pair will have exactly one path for routing. This is highly conservative and
non-adaptive scheme for routing. This Routing Table should be implemented as a Low Latency memory to reduce
